#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:9
msgid "Use your own data for this section. You will need:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:11
msgid ""
"a point vector dataset of points of interest, with point names and "
"multiple categories"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:13
msgid "a line vector dataset of roads"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:14
msgid "a polygon vector dataset of land use (using property boundaries)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:15
msgid "a visual-spectrum image (such as an aerial photograph)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:16
msgid ""
"a DEM (downloadable from `this URL <http://srtm.csi.cgiar.org/>`_ if you "
"don't have your own)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:20
msgid "Create a base map"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:22
msgid ""
"Before doing any data analysis, you will need a base map, which will "
"provide your analysis result with context."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:26
msgid "Add the point layer"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:28
msgid ""
"Add in the point layer. Based on the level that you're doing the course "
"at, do only what is listed in the appropriate section below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:32
#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:69
#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:102
msgid "|basic|"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:34
msgid ""
"Label the points according to a unique attribute, such as place names.  "
"Use a small font and keep the labels inconspicuous. The information "
"should be available, but shouldn't be a main feature of the map."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:37
msgid ""
"Classify the points themselves into different colors based on a category."
" For example, categories could include \"tourist destination\", \"police "
"station\", and \"town center\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:42
#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:75
#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:107
msgid "|moderate|"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:44
msgid "Do the same as the |basic| section."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:45
msgid ""
"Classify the point size by importance: the more significant a feature, "
"the larger its point. However, don't exceed the point size of "
":kbd:`2.00`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:47
msgid ""
"For features that aren't located at a single point (for example, "
"provincial/regional names, or town names at a large scale), don't assign "
"any point at all."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:52
#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:89
#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:114
msgid "|hard|"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:54
msgid ""
"Don't use point symbols to symbolize the layer at all. Instead, use "
"labels centered over the points; the point symbols themselves should have"
" no size."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:56
msgid ""
"Use :guilabel:`Data defined settings` to style the labels into meaningful"
" categories."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:58
msgid ""
"Add appropriate columns to the attribute data if necessary. When doing "
"so, don't create fictional data - rather, use the :guilabel:`Field "
"Calculator` to populate the new columns, based on appropriate existing "
"values in the dataset."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:64
msgid "Add the line layer"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:66
msgid "Add the road layer and then change its symbology. Don't label the roads."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:71
msgid ""
"Change the road symbology to a light color with a broad line. Make it "
"somewhat transparent as well."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:77
msgid ""
"Create a symbol with multiple symbol layers. The resulting symbol should "
"look like a real road. You can use a simple symbol for this; for example,"
" a black line with a thin white solid line running down the center. It "
"can be more elaborate as well, but the resulting map should not look too "
"busy."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:81
msgid ""
"If your dataset has a high density of roads at the scale you want to show"
" the map at, you should have two road layers: the elaborate road-like "
"symbol, and a simpler symbol at smaller scales. (Use scale-based "
"visibility to make them switch out at appropriate scales.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:85
msgid ""
"All symbols should have multiple symbol layers. Use symbols to make them "
"display correctly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:91
msgid "Do the same as in the |moderate| section above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:92
msgid ""
"In addition, roads should be classified. When using realistic road-like "
"symbols, each type of road should have an appropriate symbol; for "
"example, a highway should appear to have two lanes in either direction."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:97
msgid "Add the polygon layer"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:99
msgid "Add the land use layer and change its symbology."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:104
msgid "Classify the layer according to land use. Use solid colors."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:109
msgid ""
"Classify the layer according to land use. Where appropriate, incorporate "
"symbol layers, different symbol types, etc. Keep the results looking "
"subdued and uniform, however. Keep in mind that this will be part of a "
"backdrop!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:116
msgid ""
"Use rule-based classification to classify the land use into general "
"categories, such as \"urban\", \"rural\", \"nature reserve\", etc."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:120
msgid "Create the raster backdrop"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:122
msgid ""
"Create a hillshade from the DEM, and use it as an overlay for a "
"classified version of the DEM itself. You could also use the "
":guilabel:`Relief` plugin (as shown in the lesson on plugins)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:127
msgid "Finalize the base map"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:129
msgid ""
"Using the resources above, create a base map using some or all of the "
"layers. This map should include all the basic information needed to "
"orient the user, as well as being visually unified / \"simple\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:134
msgid "Analyze the data"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:136
msgid "You are looking for a property that satisfies certain criteria."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:137
msgid "You can decide on your own criteria, which you must document."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:138
msgid "There are some guidelines for these criteria:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:140
msgid "the target property should be of (a) certain type(s) of land use"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:141
msgid "it should be within a given distance from roads, or be crossed by a road"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:142
msgid ""
"it should be within a given distance from some category of points, like a"
" hospital for example"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:146
msgid "|moderate| / |hard|"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:148
msgid ""
"Include raster analysis in your results. Consider at least one derived "
"property of the raster, such as its aspect or slope."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:152
msgid "Final Map"
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:154
msgid ""
"Use the :guilabel:`Map Composer` to create a final map, which "
"incorporates your analysis results."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:156
msgid ""
"Include this map in a document along with your documented criteria. If "
"the map has become too visually busy due to the added layer(s), deselect "
"the layers which you feel are the least necessary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../source/docs/training_manual/assessment/index.rst:159
msgid "Your map must include a title and a legend."
msgstr ""

